## 1. First-time setup (run this yourself)

You — the agent — are responsible for getting the CLI working. The user only
needs to click Approve in the browser once. Install into a dedicated venv at
`~/.dc-portalctl/venv` so it never collides with the project's own
dependencies.

```bash
# 1. One-time: create the dedicated venv and install the CLI into it.
#    Idempotent — safe to re-run; upgrades the CLI in place.
python3 -m venv ~/.dc-portalctl/venv
~/.dc-portalctl/venv/bin/pip install --upgrade pip
~/.dc-portalctl/venv/bin/pip install --upgrade 'device-connect-server[portal]'

# 2. Put the venv's bin on PATH for this shell.
#    (Add this line to ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc to persist it across sessions.)
export PATH="$HOME/.dc-portalctl/venv/bin:$PATH"

# 3. Point dc-portalctl at this portal.
export DEVICE_CONNECT_PORTAL_URL={{ portal_url }}

# 4. Browser-mediated login. Prints a verification URL — show it to the user
#    and ask them to click Approve. The CLI polls for ~10 minutes (matches the
#    server-side request TTL); if it times out, just rerun the command. On
#    success the token is cached at ~/.config/dc-portalctl/token; subsequent
#    commands pick it up automatically.
dc-portalctl auth login

# 5. Confirm.
dc-portalctl auth me
```

**If `dc-portalctl: command not found` after a clean install,** your PyPI
release is older than this playbook — only the server-side `dc-portal` entry
point landed. Install editable from source as a fallback:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/arm/device-connect.git /tmp/device-connect
~/.dc-portalctl/venv/bin/pip install -e '/tmp/device-connect/packages/device-connect-server[portal]'
```

**macOS python.org framework Python only** (not Homebrew, not pyenv, not
the system `/usr/bin/python3`): the framework build ships without a
populated trust store, so the first HTTPS call fails with `SSL:
CERTIFICATE_VERIFY_FAILED`. (The python.org installer also ships an
`Install Certificates.command` script that does roughly this same fix —
running it once is the other way out.) `dc-portalctl` uses `aiohttp`,
which reads `SSL_CERT_FILE` (not the `requests`-specific
`REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE`). `certifi` is not a declared dependency of the
`[portal]` extra — install it explicitly into the same venv, then point
`SSL_CERT_FILE` at its bundle:

```bash
~/.dc-portalctl/venv/bin/pip install --upgrade certifi
export SSL_CERT_FILE=$(~/.dc-portalctl/venv/bin/python -c "import certifi; print(certifi.where())")
```

### Token scopes

- `devices:read` — list/describe devices
- `devices:provision` — create / decommission devices
- `devices:credentials` — re-download or rotate device credentials
- `devices:invoke` — call functions
- `events:read` — read event streams
- `admin:tenants` / `admin:*` — admin only; do not request unless you are admin

`401 invalid_token` → token revoked or expired; rerun `dc-portalctl auth
login`. `403` → token lacks the scope; mint a new one at the portal's
`/coding-agents` page (see Section 9).

### CI / non-interactive use

Skip the login flow entirely — mint a token at the portal's `/coding-agents`
page and set:

```bash
export DEVICE_CONNECT_PORTAL_URL={{ portal_url }}
export DEVICE_CONNECT_PORTAL_TOKEN=dcp_xxxxx_yyyyy
```

If your sandbox blocks `python3 -m venv` and `pipx`, fall back to direct HTTP
against `${DEVICE_CONNECT_PORTAL_URL}/api/agent/v1/*` (see Appendix A).

